05711nam a22007695i 9780226705514DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20202020ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019052057  a9780226705514  a(DE-B1597)566936  a(OCoLC)1175589561  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aBL2532.O23bC76 2020 4aBL2532.O23bC76 2021 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a299.672231 aCrosson, J. Brent, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aExperiments with Power :bObeah and the Remaking of Religion in Trinidad /cJ. Brent Crosson. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b27 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aClass 200: New Studies in Religion00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tPreface -- tIntroduction -- tPART ONE: THE DEPTHS -- tInterlude 1. Number Twenty-One Junction -- t1 What Obeah Does Do: Religion, Violence, and Law -- tInterlude 2. In the Valley of Dry Bones -- t2 Experiments with Justice: On Turning in the Grave -- tInterlude 3. To Balance the Load -- t3 Electrical Ethics: On Turning the Other Cheek -- tPART TWO: THE NATIONS -- tInterlude 4. Where the Ganges Meets the Nile, I -- t4 Blood Lines: Race, Sacrifice, and the Making of Religion -- tInterlude 5. Where the Ganges Meets the Nile, II -- t5. A Tongue between Nations: Spiritual Work, Secularism, and the Art of Crossover -- tPART THREE: THE HEIGHTS -- tInterlude 6: Arlena’s haunting -- t6 High Science -- tEpilogue: The Ends of Tolerance -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 2011, Trinidad declared a state of emergency. This massive state intervention lasted for 108 days and led to the rounding up of over 7,000 people in areas the state deemed “crime hot spots.” The government justified this action and subsequent police violence on the grounds that these measures were restoring “the rule of law.” In this milieu of expanded policing powers, protests occasioned by police violence against lower-class black people have often garnered little sympathy. But in an improbable turn of events, six officers involved in the shooting of three young people were charged with murder at the height of the state of emergency. To explain this, the host of Crime Watch, the nation’s most popular television show, alleged that there must be a special power at work: obeah. From eighteenth-century slave rebellions to contemporary responses to police brutality, Caribbean methods of problem-solving “spiritual work” have been criminalized under the label of “obeah.” Connected to a justice-making force, obeah remains a crime in many parts of the anglophone Caribbean. In Experiments with Power, J. Brent Crosson addresses the complex question of what obeah is. Redescribing obeah as “science” and “experiments,” Caribbean spiritual workers unsettle the moral and racial foundations of Western categories of religion. Based on more than a decade of conversations with spiritual workers during and after the state of emergency, this book shows how the reframing of religious practice as an experiment with power transforms conceptions of religion and law in modern nation-states.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aJusticexReligious aspects. 0aObeah (Cult)zTrinidad and TobagozTrinidad. 0aReligion and sociologyzTrinidad and TobagozTrinidad. 0aTrinidadiansxReligion. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican diaspora.  aAfricana religions.  aCaribbean.  aTrinidad.  aanthropology.  acolonialism.  acritical race theory.  aobeah.  apolice violence.  areligious studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iT